# TypeScript instructions

TypeScript-specific rules for this project. Load these *in addition
to* the general instructions in `../general/`. The TypeScript file
wins for TS code where the two might disagree.

| File | When to load |
| --- | --- |
| `style.md` | Always when writing TS. Naming, formatting, doc comments, modules. |
| `tooling.md` | Whenever a dependency changes or you run a TS command. Package manager, tsc, ESLint/Biome, Vitest. |
| `design.md` | Whenever you model new types or modules. Strict mode mindset, branded types, discriminated unions. |
| `patterns.md` | When you reach for a TS pattern — Result type, exhaustive matching, dependency injection, factory. |
| `code-smells.md` | When you spot — or are about to write — common TS anti-patterns (`any`, deep optional chains, etc.). |
| `testing.md` | Whenever you write or run TS tests. Vitest, fast-check, AAA. |

## Reading order

1. `style.md` (the baseline).
2. `tooling.md` (so you can run anything).
3. `design.md` and `patterns.md` (the modelling toolbox).
4. `code-smells.md` (what to refactor against).
5. `testing.md` (the test discipline).

## External authorities

- [TypeScript Handbook](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/intro.html) —
  the official language reference.
- [Google TypeScript Style Guide](https://google.github.io/styleguide/tsguide.html) —
  baseline style.
- *Effective TypeScript* (Dan Vanderkam) — pragmatic idioms.
- *Total TypeScript* (Matt Pocock) — type-first thinking, discriminated
  unions, branded types, type architectures.
- [type-fest](https://github.com/sindresorhus/type-fest) — battle-tested
  type utilities.
